    ```java
import java.util.*;

public int maxNodesWithoutRestricted(int n, int[][] edges, int[] restricted) {
    Map<Integer, List<Integer>> tree = new HashMap<>();
    Set<Integer> blockedNodes = new HashSet<>();
    for (int r : restricted) blockedNodes.add(r);

    for (int[] edge : edges) {
        tree.putIfAbsent(edge[0], new ArrayList<>());
        tree.putIfAbsent(edge[1], new ArrayList<>());
        tree.get(edge[0]).add(edge[1]);
        tree.get(edge[1]).add(edge[0]);
    }

    int[] maxNodes = new int[1];

    dfs(0, 1, -1, tree, blockedNodes, maxNodes);
    return maxNodes[0];
}

private void dfs(int node, int depth, int parent, Map<Integer, List<Integer>> tree, Set<Integer> blockedNodes, int[] maxNodes) {
    if (blockedNodes.contains(node)) return;
    maxNodes[0] = Math.max(maxNodes[0], depth);
    for (int child : tree.get(node)) {
        if (child != parent) dfs(child, depth + 1, node, tree, blockedNodes, maxNodes);
    }
}
```    
    1. Create an adjacency list (i.e., a data structure representing the tree) from the edges.
2. Convert the list of restricted nodes to a set to efficiently check if a node is restricted.
3. Use depth-first search (DFS) to traverse the tree from the starting node (0) while avoiding restricted nodes.
   - If a node is restricted, immediately return and stop traversing that branch.
   - Keep track of the maximum depth reached.
4. Return the maximum depth found in the DFS traversal as the answer.
